<span id="freeTextContainer6071051590000261485">This novel should&apos;ve been called <i>I&apos;m Not Racist, But--</i>. Crichton&apos;s wise men rant against the Japanese as copiously as his straw men do, and their arguments are functionally identical. By all means, he says, paint them with a broad brush, say they&apos;re schemers, insist they spell our doom, but good Lord, don&apos;t call them &quot;nips&quot;! That&apos;s bigoted!<br/><br/>Other times it seems like Crichton isn&apos;t even trying not to be racist. The whodunit that fills the first half of the book concerns a beautiful young American </span>
  <span id="freeText6071051590000261485" style="display:none">This novel should've been called <i>I'm Not Racist, But--</i>. Crichton's wise men rant against the Japanese as copiously as his straw men do, and their arguments are functionally identical. By all means, he says, paint them with a broad brush, say they're schemers, insist they spell our doom, but good Lord, don't call them "nips"! That's bigoted!<br /><br />Other times it seems like Crichton isn't even trying not to be racist. The whodunit that fills the first half of the book concerns a beautiful young American woman found raped and strangled in an LA office building owned by a powerful Japanese corporation. That a character makes a self-aware remark about the obvious symbolism only makes things worse. The ensuing investigation is conducted by a Peabody-and-Sherman sort of duo who rather than going on clues or even hunches, use stereotypes to trail the culprit. This is eventually dropped when said technique nets them actual evidence, but the message is clear: racial profiling will get you everywhere.<br /><br />Crichton's known as a master of the "page turner", but here even the pace and structure are wonky. The first half is good murder mystery stuff, laced with (ostensibly) factual information about Japanese business and now-quaint but once cutting-edge surveillance and security tech. Then that falls away suddenly, and the plot becomes a downright slog of a water-treading procedural with confusing and boring political asides. The final act really picks up again with some great should-have-seen-it-coming twists but only because it resumes the murder-mystery thread.<br /><br />The book's also notably misogynist. One female character is the protagonist's archetypally bitchy ex-wife, a lawyer who's so wrapped up in her career as to be a unfit mother for their daughter. Another woman falsely accuses him of molesting her child. The "strong woman", a part-Japanese computer whiz, plays a considerable role in the story, but mostly exists to vouch for Japan's prejudice against foreigners (Crichton repeatedly calls them "the most racist people on Earth") and to provide the sorriest attempt at sexual tension I've ever read. In the world of Rising Sun, women are either spiteful, subservient, distractingly hot, or dead.<br /><br />Japan, of course, lost interest in buying up America, and it was no thanks to fearmongerers like Crichton. But, and call me a frothing radical if you must, I'm not even sure his worst-case scenario would be all that bad. Japan's economic dominance of America would... allow them to exert a certain degree of hegemony, presumably? So what? America's got identity to spare. And it's not like we didn't have it coming. God forbid, he said sarcastically, we fall victim to environmentally conscious, confoundingly polite oppressors. I'm kidding, kind of. But Even the dirtiest deeds committed by the Japanese of Rising Sun are nothing systemic power isn't guilty of perpetrating against us under a more familiar flag.</span>
